<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEPPERDINE MAKES IT TO NCAA TOURNAMENT BY BEATING SAN DIEGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROB FERNAS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Despite Pepperdine's domination of San Diego in recent seasons, the last thing 
Coach Tom Asbury expected Monday night was an easy game. 
</P>
<P>
 He was right. 
</P>
<P>
 San Diego gave Pepperdine all it could handle as the Waves rallied from an 
eight-point halftime deficit to gain a 56-53 victory and advance to the NCAA 
tournament for the third time in four seasons by winning the West Coast 
Conference tournament at Santa Clara. 
</P>
<P>
 The Waves entered the WCC tournament final having won seven in a row and 12 of 
the last 13 meetings against the Toreros, including victories of 10 and 19 
points this season. 
</P>
<P>
 "But that does not amount to anything," Asbury said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, Pepperdine had enough in the end. 
</P>
<P>
 Dana Jones' close-range basket with 1:42 to play gave the Waves the lead for 
good, 54-53, and Damin Lopez added two free throws with 20 seconds left. San 
Diego guard David Fizdale missed badly on a three-point shot with one second 
left. 
</P>
<P>
 Jones scored 11 of his 17 points in the second half and was selected the 
tournament's most valuable player. The Waves (19-10), gaining their seventh 
consecutive victory, forced several steals in the second half to help turn the 
game around.  
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine took its first lead, 42-41, on a free throw by Jones with 8:17 to 
play, but San Diego (18-11) answered with a three-point play by center Chris 
Grant, and a 7-0 run to lead, 48-42, with a little less than seven minutes 
left. 
</P>
<P>
 The Waves came back to tie the score, 52-52, with a 6-0 run capped by Lopez's 
layup with 3:25 left. 
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine's lack of depth was a concern at the outset. The Waves entered the 
tournament in Santa Clara with eight injury-free players and Asbury feared it 
would dwindle to seven because of a slight concussion suffered by starting 
forward LeRoi O'Brien in Sunday's semifinal victory over San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
 O'Brien started and made the Waves' first basket, but it was by no means an 
encouraging beginning. 
</P>
<P>
 San Diego led by controlling the middle and strong outside shooting. The 
Toreros outrebounded Pepperdine, 23-18, and made four three-pointers in the 
first half, two by guard Neal Meyer, who had three points in the first two 
tournament games. 
</P>
<P>
 Pepperdine, meanwhile, struggled. The Waves shot 29% in the first half, the 
Toreros 34.5%. 
</P>
<P>
 Brooks Barnhard, a 6-foot-9 all-conference forward, had nine points and nine 
rebounds for San Diego. Jones paced Pepperdine with six points. 
</P>
<P>
 WCC Notes 
</P>
<P>
 San Francisco guard Gerald Walker underwent surgery Monday to repair ligament 
damage and insert a screw in his right ankle. Walker, who also suffered a 
broken right leg, was injured during Sunday's game against Pepperdine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
