<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: BANKING & FINANCE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Treasury Bill Rates Rise: The Treasury Department sold $12.6 billion of new 
three-month bills at an average discount rate of 3.52%, up from 3.40% last 
week. Another $12.6 billion of new, six-month bills was sold at an average 
discount rate of 3.75%, up from 3.61%.The three-month bill rate was the highest 
since they were sold at 3.59% on June 29, 1992. The six-month bill rate was the 
highest since they averaged 3.77% on June 22, 1992. The new discount rates 
understate the actual return to investors: 3.60% for three-month bills, with a 
$10,000 bill selling for $9,911.00, and 3.88% for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,810.40. The discount rate reflects the price discount received when 
government securities are purchased at less than face value. T-Bill Auction 
</P>
<P>
 6-month: 3.75% 
</P>
<P>
 3-month: 3.52% 
</P>
</TEXT>
