<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: SHADOW HILLS; DESPERATELY SEEKING OWNER OF AN IGUANA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF SCHNAUFER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Have you seen this face? 
</P>
<P>
 It's a mystery whether this scaly, slippery-tongued cutie is another 
earthquake-displaced victim or merely a vagabond iguana. 
</P>
<P>
 But those who found the roaming reptile two weeks ago at a Shadow Hills school 
for developmentally disabled adults say they are trying to locate the owner 
before its mug ends up on the back of a carton of iguana chow. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's frustrating," said Barbara Cone, animal management instructor at Tierra 
del Sol School, who has put out three ads in local papers and contacted animal 
shelters. "You don't often find missing iguanas." 
</P>
<P>
 This particular lizard was discovered in a pasture at the 7 1/2-acre complex, 
which provides vocational training to about 150 students and houses about 70 
animals for animal-care classes. The iguana was healthy enough to chase a horse 
before a worker nabbed it with an oven mitt. 
</P>
<P>
 Since then, however, Cone and co-workers have had problems finding the 
reptile's rightful owner. 
</P>
<P>
 Cone is keeping some of the details about the animal a mystery for a good 
reason. Iguanas, which are native to Central and South America, are becoming 
popular, but expensive, pets. Large, friendly ones can fetch up to $500. 
</P>
<P>
 "We don't want to give too many details because there are people who may just 
know the value of the animal and may call in to try to claim it," Cone said. 
</P>
<P>
 The only clues available are that it is big, green, tame and has an 
identifying scar somewhere on its body. 
</P>
<P>
 Even the gender of the animal is a mystery. "Most reptiles, you have to do an 
internal investigation to find out," said Cone. "I'm not going to do that." 
</P>
<P>
 The students, who have been caring for the iguana in a cage in the classroom, 
have even given it a name: Jade. 
</P>
<P>
 The students in Cone's class, all of whom are receiving vocational training to 
work with animals, will care for their mystery guest for at least a month, Cone 
said. Their hospitality has included providing a lamp for warmth and fresh 
vegetables. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think it's the responsibility when somebody finds a stray animal that they 
muster all forces possible to find the owner," Cone said. JEFF SCHNAUFER 
</P>
</TEXT>
