<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEST LAUNCH OF INTERCONTINENTAL MISSILE LIGHTS UP EVENING SKY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A Peacekeeper missile was successfully test-launched Monday night on a journey 
that lit up the sky for hundreds of miles. 
</P>
<P>
 The missile, carrying eight dummy warheads, was launched at 7:39 p.m. by the 
Air Force Space Command, said Staff Sgt. John B. Dendy, an Air Force spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
 The payload was delivered about 30 minutes later to the Kwajalein Missile 
Range in the South Pacific after a 4,200-mile trip. 
</P>
<P>
 "It went without a hitch," Dendy said of the launch. "The stages separated 
beautifully on the video that we saw here. The range out in the Marshall 
Islands reports that the eight test re-entry vehicles blazed in perfectly." 
</P>
<P>
 It was the 13th test launch of a Peacekeeper missile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
